<h3>How to Check if a Question Ranks on Google</h3>
<p>Copy the exact question text. Paste it into Google. If the Quora page appears in the top 5 results, that question is gold. Every answer on that page gets organic traffic from Google.</p>
<p>You can also use <a href="/blog/google-search-console-guide/">Google Search Console</a> to see which Quora pages already reference your brand or website.</p>
<h3>Finding Questions at Scale</h3>
<p><strong>Method 1: Quora search.</strong> Type your target keyword into Quora's search bar. Sort by "most viewed" or "most followed" to find high-traffic questions.</p>
<p><strong>Method 2: Google site search.</strong> Search <code>site:quora.com [your keyword]</code> on Google. This shows Quora pages that already rank for your target terms.</p>
<p><strong>Method 3: Competitor analysis.</strong> Search for your competitors' brand names on Quora. Find questions where people ask about them. Answer those questions with a balanced comparison that mentions your brand.</p>
<p><strong>Method 4: Keyword research crossover.</strong> Use the same <a href="/blog/keyword-research-for-blog-posts/">keyword research process</a> you use for blog content. Take your long-tail keywords and check if matching questions exist on Quora. If they do, answer them.</p>
<h3>Question Tracking System</h3>
<p>Create a spreadsheet with these columns: Question URL, Topic, View Count, Answer Count, Date Answered, Link Included (yes/no), and Monthly Check-In Date. Review monthly to update answers and track which ones drive traffic.</p>
